description:
Lower Rust's remaining item types:
- Constant items: const MAX: usize = 100; — compile-time constants
- Static items: static COUNTER: AtomicUsize = ...; static mut LOG: File; — global variables
- Unsafe functions: unsafe fn dangerous() { ... }
- Unsafe blocks: unsafe { ptr.read() }
- Extern blocks: extern "C" { fn sqrt(x: f64) -> f64; }
- Extern functions: extern "C" fn callback() { ... }
- Async functions: async fn fetch() -> Result { ... }
- Async blocks: async { body }
- Union definitions: union MyUnion { i: i32, f: f32 }
unsafe is a modifier on functions and a block type. extern specifies ABI. async is more common and should map to existing uir-await patterns. const/static are storage class modifiers. Unions are similar to structs but with overlapping fields.

Lower trait definitions and implementation blocks:
- Trait definitions: trait Foo { fn method(&self) -> i32; fn with_default(&self) { 42 } }
- Associated types: trait Iterator { type Item; fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item>; }
- Supertraits: trait Bar: Foo + Display { }
- Inherent impl: impl Foo { fn new() -> Self { ... } fn method(&self) { ... } }
- Trait impl: impl Display for Foo { fn fmt(&self, f: &mut Formatter) -> fmt::Result { ... } }
- impl for foreign types: impl Foo for String { ... }
Need new UIR structs: uir-trait (name, generics, supertraits, associated types, methods), uir-impl (target type, trait (optional), generics, items). Trait methods and impl items are uir-fn. impl blocks can contain associated constants and type aliases too.

Lower enum definitions and variant construction:
- Enum definitions: enum Color { Red, Green, Blue } — unit variants
- Enum with data: enum Option<T> { None, Some(T) } — variants with typed fields
- Enum with named fields: enum Shape { Circle { radius: f64 }, Rectangle { w: f64, h: f64 } }
- Enum with tuple fields: enum Result<T, E> { Ok(T), Err(E) }
- Variant construction: Color::Red, Option::Some(42), Shape::Circle { radius: 1.0 }
Need a new UIR struct (uir-enum) with uir-variant list. Each variant has name, optional data (tuple fields or named fields), optional discriminant. Variant construction via uir-call convention (e.g., uir-call (uir-symbol "Option::Some") (list value)).
